reviewText:
Fairly boring

They exclaim that you're living your life

Everything that happens to you is simply RNG based

Throughout the stages of life, childhood, teen years, adult hood, elderly years, you're put in a room (Which is simply pointless, there's nothing you can do in them other than throw things) with 4 doors, enter a door, and what happens to you in your life is explained with puppets

It's humorous, cute, but a waste of money for someone with no income like myself

If you feel like throwing money in a blender for ♥♥♥♥(s) n giggles then by all means have some fun

reviewText: Womb Room is a rather strange game. The goal of the player is simply to die. There are chances that you will die by your own means or by accident. A single run of the game will take less than 5 minutes, but there was a single run that I played that ended before it started. I started the game and died as a baby before being born.\n\nThe game is glitchy, however. All text would say Null" and nothing else. I'm sure this was supposed to be replaced with some sort of reason behind my death. Some items clip through other things or the ground. I really wanted to like this game
date:
but there's just not much to it.

I'm sure my time with the game was bad simply because I couldn't tell what was going on with the "Null" problem.

You roam around each room picking up things and setting them down. There's not much else to do in each room other than that. Then you walk through one of four doors and await your life on the other side hoping you made the right choice.

I'd give this game a go I suppose if you have time to waste
recommended: otherwise don't waste your time with it."

reviewText: I played 20 minutes of this game and knew that it needed work. First off it has no options and literally no UI once you have started the game you only have the option to quit or finish the game. Second the game is very short and has very little to no plot and with most of my outcomes my character would be dead before the teenage years. I see no point to play this game more than once and it is not worth 1.50~3.00$. I would suggest to the developer to make this game free and think about working on his coding a bit before actually selling his product.

reviewText:
Please don't buy this even for $0.50. The gameplay goes as follows.

1) You walk through one of three doors with no indication as to what any of them do.
2) A puppet says something about your life like You were born a ginger without a soul" or "You got your allowance raised"
3) You are put into a lightly furnished room with nothing to do.
4) You walk through one of four doors in the room (Absolutely nothing indicates what each one does)
5) A puppet tells you that you died or some fact about the next stage of your life if you didn't die (Seemingly randomly)
6) You are put into a room that reflects your new age
date: return to step 4 until you die.\n\nTHIS IS THE ENTIRE GAME."

reviewText: I can see where this game had potential. You are given a life. You can die at any point in that life. You go through birth, childhood, teenage years, adulthood, and your elderly stages. As mentioned in some other reviews it is all randomly generated what happens. What would make this game at least come close to the potential it had for the price, is if the rooms weren't so pointless. Perhaps if the objects you interacted with effected your room, or the doors had a more karma like variety to them and it mattered the decisions you made. All in all though you just pick whatever door, walk through it, and a puppet generates the next step in your life. If you are an achievement hunter keep in mind that all of the achievements in this game are simply rng based and some seem like a really low chance.\n\nNot really worth wasting the money on.

reviewText:
Essentially a carbon copy of an old web game that did exactly the same thing, but strictly in text. I'm not giving this a negative review because of what this game does or how it does it - but because of what it DOESN'T do.

It doesn't keep track of anything that's happened. At all.

This means that you can end up homeless, and then die from shoveling snow off the roof of your house. There is zero attention paid to the very core reason this game exists - a contiguous life story.
